04638nam a22005535i 9780226034331DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226034331  a(DE-B1597)523220  a(OCoLC)845040643  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aHIS0000002bisacsh  aNW 67002rvk1 aVoskuhl, Adelheid, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAndroids in the Enlightenment :bMechanics, Artisans, and Cultures of the Self /cAdelheid Voskuhl. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b8 halftones, 4 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tOne. Introduction: Androids, Enlightenment, and the Human-Machine Boundary -- tTwo. The Harpsichord-Playing Android; or, Clock-Making in Switzerland -- tThree. The Dulcimer-Playing Android; or, Furniture- Making in the Rhineland -- tFour. The Design of the Mechanics; or, Sentiments Replicated in Clockwork -- tFive. Poetic Engagement with Piano-Playing Women Automata -- tSix. The “Enlightenment Automaton” in the Modern Industrial Age -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe eighteenth century saw the creation of a number of remarkable mechanical androids: at least ten prominent automata were built between 1735 and 1810 by clockmakers, court mechanics, and other artisans from France, Switzerland, Austria, and the German lands. Designed to perform sophisticated activities such as writing, drawing, or music making, these “Enlightenment automata” have attracted continuous critical attention from the time they were made to the present, often as harbingers of the modern industrial age, an era during which human bodies and souls supposedly became mechanized. In Androids in the Enlightenment, Adelheid Voskuhl investigates two such automata—both depicting piano-playing women. These automata not only play music, but also move their heads, eyes, and torsos to mimic a sentimental body technique of the eighteenth century: musicians were expected to generate sentiments in themselves while playing, then communicate them to the audience through bodily motions. Voskuhl argues, contrary to much of the subsequent scholarly conversation, that these automata were unique masterpieces that illustrated the sentimental culture of a civil society rather than expressions of anxiety about the mechanization of humans by industrial technology. She demonstrates that only in a later age of industrial factory production did mechanical androids instill the fear that modern selves and societies had become indistinguishable from machines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArtisanszEuropexHistory. 0aEnlightenmentzEurope. 0aMechanical engineeringxHistory. 0aRobotsxHistory. 70(DE-601)1041966020(DE-588)4152096-8aEmpfindsamkeit2gnd 70(DE-601)1061832490(DE-588)4050208-9aRoboter2gnd 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  amachines, robots, android, mechanics, mechanical, artisan, culture, cultural, self, identity, sociology, sociological, 18th century, technology, automata, automaton, 1700s, 1800s, clockmaker, france, switzerland, europe, western, austria, german, germany, industrial, era, time period, history, historical, academic, scholarly, research, communication, performance, dulcimer, harpsichord.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022603402740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226034331423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226034331/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of C